This project was funded by a grant from the Research for Health in Humanitarian Crises (R2HC)
Programme (Grant number 14048). Elrha’s R2HC programme aims to improve health outcomes by strengthening
the evidence base for public health interventions in humanitarian crises. The R2HC programme is the product of
a strategic partnership between the UK Government (DFID) and the Wellcome Trust.
Special thanks to the volunteers who took part in this study. Thanks to Fitria Bunga
Elizabeth and Mia P. Sianturi (SKM), Hasan Tarigan (SEKBER(Sekretariat Bersama/Joint Humanitarian Secretary)),
the staff of the Center for Volcanology and Geological Hazard Mitigation (Karo Regency) and Happy Surbakti and
Loving Tarigan for all their local assistance and support with the study. Finally, thanks to the HIVE consortium
and Advisory Group members for their helpful comments during the HIVE project and Djoni Ferdiwajaya for his
assistance in recruiting local researchers to undertake the study.
The authors declare no conﬂict of interest.
